<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910730-0025</DOCNO><DOCID>910730-0025.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Recognition Equipment Inc.:   Five Shareholder Lawsuits   To Be Settled in Accord</HL><DATE>07/30/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2</SO><CO>   REC</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>OFFICE EQUIPMENT (OFF)</IN><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)TEXAS (TX)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Recognition Equipment Inc., Dallas, said it agreed to paya portion of the plaintiffs' legal fees to settle fiveshareholder lawsuits filed against it in federal court in theDistrict of Columbia.   The maker of document-processing equipment said the suits,which sought class-action status, charged that the companyviolated securities laws in its public statements related toits attempts to win a U.S. Postal Service contract in themid-1980s. The suits were based on allegations made againstthe company and two former top officers in a criminalproceeding. The company and the officers were acquitted inNovember 1989.</LP><TEXT>   Under the settlement, Recognition denied any wrongdoing,but said it agreed to pay an &quot;immaterial&quot; amount for legalfees and to maintain its ethics program until 1993. Theprogram includes a company ethics policy, education ofemployees, and a hotline.   The company said it now has settled all shareholderlawsuits related to the Postal Service contract but onelawsuit filed by a customer is still pending.</TEXT></DOC>